snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Julien, THIS IS URGENT and I really and sincerely hope you read this.
I tried to find an email ID on your and Jenna's Instagram/Twitter so that I could contact you, but there was nothing. This is the only way I can send this message across. One of my friends is a YouTuber, and she was recently in a situation that I'm sure all YouTubers have been in or are in.

She was at her house when she heard random people screaming down the street in front of her yard. She went to check and they were all teenage boys and girls; her fans .
She did take one picture with them, but then politely asked them to leave. Luckily, they were nice enough and they understood her concern, but not everyone does that.

She asked them how they found her address, and they told her about this website called WhitePages (https://www.whitepages.com/).

It's a very dangerous website that gives you extremely private details about people; like their name, age, address (previous and current), their family members and the same details of said family members too.

I remember watching your video "don't come to our house" posted sometime in 2017. I'm really sorry for infringing upon your privacy by looking up if your name was on WhitePages, but I genuinely am a big fan of yours and Jenna and I HAD to let you know. Your details, including Jenna's name and her family, your parents, your previous address and everything else is on there. I'd strongly suggest contacting the website and having all your details taken down, and I think that's the most popular way how fans end up finding out where YouTubers live.

People can literally pay money on WhitePages based on how comprehensive of details they want. I didn't even pay(I wouldn't ever), and they have your address open to the public for free. Please take action. I would have linked the page with your details on here, but this is a comment section so I'm not going to. I'm really sorry for looking it up but I am genuinely concerned, especially after the incident with my friend. I really appreciate you and Jenna, hence why I'm saying this. Please forgive me.

Regards,
A concerned fan

snippet.textDisplay:
Honestly as a child of a Mexican mother, this is actually not bad at all. It looks pretty good!

Just a tip for next time (this is how my family makes pozole rojo): take the seeds off the chiles before putting them in water, next time boil the chiles with the water so you can also add that to the adobo sauce to thin it out and adds a bit more flavor. Also next time add oregano as a topping and instead of tortilla, try tostadas and sour cream in top of the tostada.

snippet.textDisplay:
I usually don’t comment but hispanic here but this video made me really happy so I wanted to share my thoughts.

While it’s not perfect, there are a few things I would change (Mostly encouraging to buy some Goya Products for seasoning because that’s where it’s at BOI) the end product, while I obviously can’t taste it, LOOKS beautiful. The color is just right, the use of the Mexican corn made me really happy (even if it’s too white and kinda off looking but that isn’t your fault) the presentation is beautiful.

Also how the video it self was handled is just... so good. I’m not Mexican myself, I’m Puerto Rican, but me and my mother have been taught how to make Pozole from a family friend who is Mexican, and we frequently go visit them, so seeing appreciation for a culture I have throughly enjoyed and felt welcomed and at home in makes me happy. THIS is the perfect example of cultural appreciation, not appropriation. I hope you make more dishes from other hispanic cultures in the future, because I’ll know you do great, because for the first time making it, it looks pretty bomb as hell.
